== Questions to Ask When Choosing Your Birth Setting

Whether you're interviewing hospitals, birth centers, or midwives, these questions help you understand what to expect and make an informed choice.

=== Questions for Hospitals and Hospital-Based Providers

*Intervention rates:*
- What is your cesarean rate? (Ask for overall rate and rate for low-risk first-time mothers specifically)
- What is your episiotomy rate?
- What percentage of your patients are induced?
- What is your vacuum/forceps delivery rate?

*Labor and delivery policies:*
- Can I eat and drink during labor?
- Can I move freely during labor, or am I required to stay in bed?
- What is your policy on continuous fetal monitoring vs. intermittent monitoring?
- What labor positions do you support? Can I labor and deliver in positions other than on my back?
- Do you have wireless monitoring so I can move around?
- Can I use a birth tub or shower during labor?

*Birth practices:*
- Do you support delayed cord clamping? For how long?
- Can I have immediate skin-to-skin contact after birth, even if I have a cesarean?
- What happens to my baby right after birth? When are routine procedures done?
- Do you separate mothers and babies for routine care, or can everything be done in the room?

*Provider continuity:*
- Will you be at my birth, or do you rotate with other providers?
- If you rotate, how many providers should I meet before labor?
- Who makes decisions if you're not available?

*Cesarean questions (if applicable):*
- Under what circumstances would you recommend a cesarean?
- What is your policy on VBACs (vaginal birth after cesarean)?
- Can my partner be present for a cesarean?
- Can I have skin-to-skin in the operating room?

=== Questions for Birth Centers

*Qualifications and safety:*
- Are you accredited by CABC (Commission for the Accreditation of Birth Centers)?
- What are your midwives' credentials? (CNM, CM, or CPM?)
- How long have you been practicing? How many births have you attended?

*Transfer protocols:*
- What is your transfer rate? (Overall and broken down by first-time vs. experienced mothers)
- Which hospital do you transfer to?
- Do you have a collaborative agreement with physicians there?
- What happens during a transfer? Do you come with me?
- How often are transfers emergencies vs. non-urgent?

*Who qualifies:*
- What conditions would risk me out of birth center care?
- Do you accept VBACs? (Most don't)
- What happens if I develop complications during pregnancy?

*Cost and insurance:*
- What is your total fee, and what does it include?
- Do you accept my insurance?
- If not, can you provide a superbill for me to submit for reimbursement?
- What happens to my cost if I transfer?

=== Questions for Home Birth Midwives

*Credentials and experience:*
- What is your credential? (CNM, CM, or CPM?)
- Are you licensed in this state?
- How many births have you attended? How many as primary attendant?
- What is your transfer rate?
- Have you ever had a maternal death or neonatal death? (If yes, what happened?)

*Emergency preparedness:*
- What emergency equipment do you bring? (Oxygen, IV fluids, hemorrhage medications, newborn resuscitation equipment?)
- What is your protocol for postpartum hemorrhage?
- What is your protocol for newborn resuscitation?
- How far are you from the nearest hospital?

*Transfer protocols:*
- Which hospital would I transfer to?
- Do you have a relationship with physicians there?
- What situations would require transfer?
- Do you stay with me during and after transfer?

*Scope of practice:*
- Can you provide prenatal labs, or do I need to go elsewhere?
- Can you do ultrasounds, or will I need to arrange those separately?
- Can you prescribe medications if needed? (Depends on credential and state)
- What postpartum care do you provide? For how long?

*Practical details:*
- Do you bring a second attendant? Is that included in your fee?
- What supplies do I need to provide?
- What is your on-call policy? How do I reach you when labor starts?

